I see now. The ApplicationUserService extends UserManager<ApplicationUser>, which is from Microsoft.AspNet.Identity. The Create method is not defined in this service, so it's using the base class method from UserManager.

The UserManager.Create(user, password) method returns an IdentityResult, not the user object. This is the key issue!

The correct code should be:
```csharp
var result = userService.Create(user, model.Password);
if (result.Succeeded)
{
    // User created successfully
    return RedirectToAction("Edit", new { Id = user.Id });
}
else
{
    // Handle errors
    foreach (var error in result.Errors)
    {
        ModelState.AddModelError("", error);
    }
    return View(model);
}
```

The current code is:
1. Not capturing the IdentityResult from the Create call
2. Checking if user == null (which will never be true since the object was just created)
3. Not checking the actual result of the creation operation

This is why the user is not being created - the Create method is probably failing (returning Succeeded = false), but the code isn't checking the result. It's trying to redirect to Edit with a user that has no ID (or a default ID), which causes issues.

